@Article{delbrassine1988,
  author    = {Delbrassine, S. and Rasmont, P.},
  title     = {Contribution \`{a} l'\'{e}tude de la pollinisation du colza, \emph{Brassica napus} {L}. var. \emph{oleifera} ({Moench}) {Delile}, en {Belgique}},
  journal   = {Bulletin des recherches agronomiques de {Gembloux}},
  year      = {1988},
  volume    = {23},
  pages     = {123--152},
  abstract  = {[Translated] The authors studied insect pollinators of canola (Brassica napus L. var oleifera) Delile, in 4 locations of Wallonie (southern Belgium) from 1984 to 1985.

The most important species of pollinators were social Apidae: Apis mellifera, Bombus terrestris, B. lucorum, B. cryptarum, and Pyrobombus lapidarius. Honeybees visit the nectaries of canola using 3 different methods. In the "climbing-over" method, after the first nectary, the bee climbed over the style to visit the second. In the "bypassing" method, after the first nectary, the bee went around the style to get to the second nectary. In the "inserting" method, the bee inserted its tongue from the outside of the corolla between the base of the petals (nectar theiving). Only the first method deposited pollen on the stigma. Bumblebees used only the first method.

