  year      = {2013},
  volume    = {19},
  number    = {8},
  pages     = {2348--2359},
  abstract  = {Variation in species’ responses to abiotic phenological cues under climate change may cause changes in temporal
overlap among interacting taxa, with potential demographic consequences. Here, we examine associations between
the abiotic environment and plant-pollinator phenological synchrony using a long-term syrphid fly-flowering phenology
dataset (1992-2011). Degree-days above freezing, precipitation, and timing of snow melt were investigated as
