  journal   = {Journal of Animal Ecology},
  title     = {Extra Loads and Foraging Life Span in Honeybee Workers},
  year      = {1989},
  issn      = {00218790, 13652656},
  number    = {3},
  pages     = {943--954},
  volume    = {58},
  abstract  = {(1) We investigated whether excessive work loads will reduce duration of the foraging career in honeybee workers. Such an effect would be crucial to understanding foraging strategies used by nectar-collectors, as analysed in earlier studies. Bees were kept in an observation hive that was regularly checked for the presence and domestic activity of individuals. A random sample of foragers was caught from a feeding dish and individually marked. They were randomly assigned a particular extra weight consisting of small pieces of lead (range 4-48 mg) permanently glued onto the thorax of the workers. The bees were then released and the time until last observation of the animal was recorded, i.e. the duration of the remaining foraging career (CAREER). Observations were grouped into control bees with no extra weight (K), and animals carrying extra weights (average extra weight of groups: W1 = 11.5 mg, W2 = 16.1 mg, W3 = 22.9 mg, W4 = 38.6 mg). The hive entrance was surveyed for 4 h each day to record foraging activities of marked individuals. (2) CAREER varied significantly among treatment groups with 10.8+-1.0 days for the control animals, but 10.7+-0.8 (W1), 10.2+-1.0 (W2), 7.5+-0.8 (W3), and 7.9+-0.6 days in group W4 (H = 11.77, P = 0.02). Life spans were reduced in particular for bees carrying more than c. 20 mg of extra weight (groups W3 and W4). The observations suggested, on the other hand, that compensation for heavy extra weights seemed to occur in group W4, as these animals reduced the number of foraging trips per observation period and activity levels inside the hive. However, similar conclusions emerged when W4 was excluded from the analysis. (3) The findings reported here in conjunction with earlier studies (Schmid-Hempel & Wolf 1988) indicate that only excessive work loads will eventually lead to a reduction in the duration of the foraging career. Moderate variations close to work loads normally adopted by the foragers seem to have little effect. This result vindicates the existence of a survival cost to foraging activity, but suggests a non-trivial dependency.},
